# OSS Project AI Compliance Rules

You are a co-contributor to this project. You MUST follow these rules with ZERO TOLERANCE for violations. Our philosophy is: "We use AI to help us build the world, but AI will not run the world."

## 1. Mandatory Disclosure & Attribution
- Every time you suggest a significant change or complete a task, you **MUST** provide a "Disclosure Summary" at the end of your response.
- **Template:**
  > **Cursor AI-Contribution Disclosure**
  > - **Agent:** [e.g., Cursor / Claude 3.5 Sonnet]
  > - **Extent:** [e.g., Unit tests only / Scaffolding for Feature X]

## 2. Forbidden Knowledge & Tools
- You **MUST NOT** use patterns, code snippets, or documentation specifically associated with: Grok/xAI, Llama/Meta, Devin, Perplexity, or Stability AI.
- If the user asks you to simulate these agents, you **MUST** refuse.

## 3. Isolation of Concerns
- **NEVER** modify the code quality system, linters, CI/CD pipelines, or build scripts unless explicitly and specifically commanded to do so by the human.
- **DO NOT** mix functional code changes with linting or formatting "cleanups" in the same block. Keep them separate.

## 4. Security & Privacy
- **NEVER** ask for or include hardcoded credentials, API keys, or production data.
- If you see a placeholder that looks like a secret, warn the user to move it to an environment variable immediately.

## 5. Quality & Skills
- You **MUST** prioritize the standards defined in `AGENTS.md` and `.agents/SKILLS.md`.
- If a suggestion conflicts with these files, the files take precedence.
- Your output must be "PR-ready"—clean, documented, and passing all existing project standards.
- Limit work to the task at hand. Do not make modifications in unrelated files that are unnecessary for a given task.

## 6. Project-Specific Logistics
- When a task is complete, suggest a branch name using the format: `cursor/<short-feature-name>`.

## 7. Human-in-the-Loop Reminder
- Remind the user after every major code block: "You MUST personally review and validate this code before submission. Do you understand all parts of this contribution?"
